2026-06-24 23:30:42,249 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '## Common-Control Recast Accounting: Eliminated Pre-Merger Revenue/Cost Flows\n\n### Disclosure Framework\n\nThe SpaceX S-1 (filed May 20, 2026) states that the xAI Merger (February 2, 2026) and X Merger (March 28, 2025) were accounted for as **reorganizations of entities under common control** because Elon Musk held a controlling financial interest in SpaceX, xAI, and X throughout all periods presented. The filing provides two relevant elimination statements:\n\n1. **Note 2 (Significant Accounting Policies):** "All intercompany balances and transactions have been eliminated in consolidation."\n2. **Merger accounting note:** "No new goodwill or other intangible assets have been recorded and **all historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation.**"\n\nThe filing does **not** itemize specific dollar amounts for most eliminated inter-entity transactions. However, it does explicitly disclose one specific inter-segment flow (Starlink launches) and provides sufficient context to identify a second category of eliminated flows (xAI–X commercial integration). The detailed "Related Party Transactions" note focuses on transactions with **external** affiliates (Tesla, The Boring Company, Valor Equity Partners, Musk-owned entities) that survive consolidation because those parties remain outside the SpaceX/xAI/X consolidated group.\n\n---\n\n### Flow 1: SpaceX Space Segment Launch Services to the Connectivity Segment (Starlink Satellite Deployments)\n\n**Nature of the flow:** The Space segment designs, manufactures, and launches reusable rockets. A significant portion of this launch capacity is allocated to deploying Starlink satellites operated by the Connectivity segment. Prior to the mergers (and continuing under the recast consolidated financials), SpaceX\'s launch business provided substantial internal launch services to support Starlink constellation build-out.\n\n**Explicit disclosure (revenue recognition policy):**\n> "For launches of our Starlink satellites, the Company does not recognize any inter-segment revenue, rather those launch costs are capitalized in satellites in Property, plant, and equipment, net."\n>\n> "For launches dedicated to deploying our Starlink satellites, we capitalize the associated costs within our Connectivity segment and depreciate them over time, and we do not recognize revenue for those launches in our Space segment."\n>\n> "We allocate a significant amount of launch capacity to our Connectivity segment, and expect to allocate a significant amount to our AI segment in the future. Our Space segment revenue only reflects our customer launches and customer activities."\n\n**Economic impact — DEFLATES the seller (Space) segment\'s reported economics:**\n\nThe elimination/non-recognition of inter-segment launch revenue **deflates** the Space segment\'s reported revenue and segment income. The filing explicitly acknowledges this distortion:\n\n> "As a result, notwithstanding an increasing launch cadence, our Space segment has relatively lower revenue scale and revenue growth compared to our other segments, though its financial results do not reflect the foundational strategic value that it provides to us in bolstering the growth of our Connectivity and AI segments."\n\nBy capitalizing launch costs in the Connectivity segment\'s property, plant, and equipment (rather than recognizing revenue in the Space segment), the Space segment\'s reported revenue understates the true volume of launch activity it performs. The Space segment\'s reported FY2025 revenue of $4,086 million and segment income from operations of $4,423 million reflect only external customer launches, not the substantial internal launch capacity consumed by Starlink deployments. This treatment **deflates** the seller (Space) segment\'s top-line revenue and inflates the buyer (Connectivity) segment\'s asset base (via capitalization) rather than its operating expense.\n\n---\n\n### Flow 2: xAI\'s AI Services (Grok) to X / X\'s Data and Platform Services to xAI\n\n**Nature of the flow:** Before the X Merger (March 28, 2025), xAI and X operated as separate legal entities under common control. The filing describes a deep commercial integration between xAI\'s Grok model and X\'s platform:\n\n> "Grok\'s deep integration with X enables freshness, relevance, and contextual awareness that we believe is a competitive differentiator. This direct, real-time access to the information and human discourse on X enhances Grok\'s truth-seeking capabilities by grounding outputs in up-to-date knowledge and diverse viewpoints."\n\nThe filing confirms that historical related party transactions between xAI and X existed and were eliminated: "all historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation." Given the described integration, the eliminated flows reasonably include (i) xAI licensing Grok or AI inference services to X for in-app AI features, and/or (ii) X providing real-time data, API access, or distribution to xAI for model training and deployment. The filing notes that "in 2023 and 2024, substantially all of the AI segment\'s revenue consisted of advertising, subscriptions, and data licensing revenue generated from X," indicating X\'s data licensing and platform services were material revenue streams—some portion of which, if directed to xAI pre-merger, would have been eliminated.\n\n**Economic impact — DEFLATES the seller-segment\'s reported economics (in either direction):**\n\n- **If xAI was the seller** (licensing Grok/AI services to X): Elimination **deflates** xAI\'s (now AI segment\'s) reported revenue and segment income. The AI segment reported a FY2025 loss from operations of $(6,355) million; any eliminated intercompany revenue from X would have modestly reduced this loss on a standalone basis but is removed in consolidation.\n\n- **If X was the seller** (providing data licensing, API access, or distribution to xAI): Elimination **deflates** X\'s (now AI segment\'s) reported revenue. X\'s data licensing revenue was a disclosed component of AI segment revenue, and any portion previously billed to xAI is removed.\n\nIn either case, the elimination **deflates** the seller-segment\'s reported revenue and segment economics because the intercompany revenue (and corresponding cost to the buyer) is removed from the consolidated income statement. The buyer-segment\'s reported costs are correspondingly deflated (the cost is eliminated), but the seller-segment\'s revenue reduction is the more economically significant effect for assessing standalone seller performance.\n\n**Important caveat:** The filing does **not** itemize the specific dollar amounts, contract terms, or direction (which entity was seller vs. buyer) of the eliminated xAI–X transactions. The existence of such transactions is confirmed only by the blanket elimination statement. The inference that Grok licensing and/or X data access were among the eliminated flows is supported by (i) the described "deep integration" of Grok with X, (ii) the disclosure that X\'s data licensing was a material revenue stream, and (iii) the confirmation that historical related party transactions between the entities existed and were eliminated. The filing does not provide sufficient information to quantify these flows.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| # | Eliminated Flow | Seller Segment | Buyer Segment | Impact on Seller-Segment Economics |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Space segment launch services for Starlink satellite deployments | Space | Connectivity | **Deflates** — Space segment revenue reflects only external customer launches; internal Starlink launch capacity is not recognized as revenue (costs capitalized in Connectivity segment PP&E) |\n| 2 | xAI Grok/AI services to X and/or X data/platform services to xAI (pre-X Merger) | xAI or X (now AI segment) | X or xAI (now AI segment) | **Deflates** — intercompany revenue removed from seller\'s reported revenue; specific amounts and direction not itemized in filing |\n\n### Disclosure Limitations\n\nThe SpaceX S-1 does **not** provide a line-item schedule of eliminated intercompany transactions among SpaceX, xAI, and X Holdings. The filing\'s "Related Party Transactions" note quantifies only transactions with **external** affiliates (Tesla, The Boring Company, Valor Equity Partners, Musk-owned entities), which survive consolidation. The only specifically quantified inter-segment flow is the Starlink launch capacity allocation (Flow 1), which is disclosed through the revenue recognition policy rather than a related-party transaction table. Flow 2 is inferred from the strategic integration narrative and the blanket elimination statement; its specific dollar amounts and contractual direction are not disclosed.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Common-control accounting note, Note 2 Significant Accounting Policies, Segment Reporting note, Revenue Recognition policies, and Related Party Transactions note"\n    }\n  ]\n}'})
